Definition.WordDefinition: Deutoxide \Deu*tox"ide\ (?; 104), n. [Pref. deut- + oxide.] (Chem.) A compound containing in the molecule two atoms of oxygen united with some other element or radical; -- usually called {dioxide}, or less frequently, {binoxide}. [1913 Webster] ||

Dictionary.Name: The Collaborative International Dictionary of English v.0.44

Definition.WordDefinition:
Dioxide \Di*ox"ide\ (?; 104), n. [Pref. di- + oxide.] (Chem.) (a) An oxide containing two atoms of oxygen in each molecule; binoxide. (b) An oxide containing but one atom or equivalent of oxygen to two of a metal; a suboxide. [Obs.] [1913 Webster]
{Carbon dioxide}. See {Carbonic acid}, under {Carbonic}. [1913 Webster]
dioxide n : an oxide containing two atoms of oxygen in the molecule
